271
00:17:26,510 --> 00:17:27,710
They're just feigning ignorance now.

272
00:17:28,740 --> 00:17:31,650
So, if Director Ha lost Construction...

273
00:17:31,780 --> 00:17:33,680
as well as his connections at Samoel,

274
00:17:34,720 --> 00:17:36,650
then he's got nothing now. Right?

275
00:17:48,230 --> 00:17:50,060
Mr. Oh, the CEO, cried.

276
00:17:51,100 --> 00:17:52,100
- Pardon? - Pardon?

277
00:17:52,430 --> 00:17:53,969
He cried after the
chairman chewed him out...

278
00:17:53,970 --> 00:17:55,600
for failing to get WIND to go public.

279
00:17:58,940 --> 00:18:00,979
Director Ha, then you could...

280
00:18:00,980 --> 00:18:03,309
visit Samoel and try to convince them...

281
00:18:03,310 --> 00:18:05,180
I said I'd do that,

282
00:18:05,780 --> 00:18:07,450
but the chairman said to just leave it.

283
00:18:07,950 --> 00:18:10,419
Whether it goes public or not,

284
00:18:10,420 --> 00:18:11,950
he wants to scrap it altogether.

285
00:18:12,520 --> 00:18:13,520
I see.

286
00:18:13,750 --> 00:18:14,960
WIND?

287
00:18:15,260 --> 00:18:17,090
Whether it's WIND or whoever else.

288
00:18:17,560 --> 00:18:19,389
He's furious right now.

289
00:18:19,390 --> 00:18:20,390
I see.

290
00:18:21,060 --> 00:18:22,800
I guess you met with Chairman Song.

291
00:18:23,030 --> 00:18:24,230
Yes, just now.

292
00:18:25,530 --> 00:18:28,639
Why didn't WIND go public years ago?

293
00:18:28,640 --> 00:18:29,900
Why bother trying now?

294
00:18:30,040 --> 00:18:31,110
My point, exactly.

295
00:18:31,240 --> 00:18:32,709
After the pandemic,

296
00:18:32,710 --> 00:18:35,040
people who have money
are busy travelling overseas,

297
00:18:35,340 --> 00:18:37,279
while people who don't have money
are struggling to make ends meet.

298
00:18:37,280 --> 00:18:39,480
Who has time to ride a bike these days?

299
00:18:39,810 --> 00:18:42,420
I understand Mr. Oh wanted to cry.

300
00:18:42,480 --> 00:18:43,779
He didn't just want to cry.

301
00:18:43,780 --> 00:18:45,590
He cried his eyes out.

302
00:18:46,690 --> 00:18:48,590
- My goodness. - About Director Ha.

303
00:18:49,290 --> 00:18:51,530
Isn't it partially his fault too?

304
00:18:52,230 --> 00:18:54,129
He should've bought
something that could go public.

305
00:18:54,130 --> 00:18:56,200
He knew it was hopeless,
but he dumped it on me.

306
00:18:56,760 --> 00:18:58,100
Now, he's acting like
it's none of his business.

307
00:18:58,530 --> 00:18:59,900
I really can't stand him.

308
00:19:00,900 --> 00:19:02,440
I'll see what I can do,

309
00:19:03,340 --> 00:19:04,610
so calm down.

310
00:19:04,740 --> 00:19:06,940
You see, I...

311
00:19:08,410 --> 00:19:09,880
This is my second year.

312
00:19:10,710 --> 00:19:12,150
Because of the contract renewal,

313
00:19:13,180 --> 00:19:15,950
I put a lot of effort into the Saipan deal.

314
00:19:17,150 --> 00:19:18,320
But out of the blue,

315
00:19:19,120 --> 00:19:20,850
he blindsided me with
this WIND thing. My gosh.

316
00:19:21,460 --> 00:19:22,959
To list a company on the stock market,

317
00:19:22,960 --> 00:19:24,830
it's important to consider
what's happening on the market.

318
00:19:24,990 --> 00:19:25,990
If the market is doing well,

319
00:19:25,991 --> 00:19:27,289
WIND will have no problem.

320
00:19:27,290 --> 00:19:29,400
But the market is doing
so badly these days,

321
00:19:29,530 --> 00:19:31,999
so you need to show that the
company's situation will improve.

322
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:34,500
However, WIND's sales have dropped sharply.

323
00:19:34,700 --> 00:19:37,199
So, you had no choice but
to submit a negative report.

324
00:19:37,200 --> 00:19:40,610
Right. If it fails after I vouch
for it knowing it won't work out,

325
00:19:41,640 --> 00:19:44,039
we'll all be doomed.

326
00:19:44,040 --> 00:19:45,110
You're right.

327
00:19:45,710 --> 00:19:47,779
What are our options with Samoel?

328
00:19:47,780 --> 00:19:49,919
According to the put with Samoel,

329
00:19:49,920 --> 00:19:51,949
the closing price of Sanin's stock price...

330
00:19:51,950 --> 00:19:54,320
has to be lower than 100 dollars
for 20 consecutive business days.

331
00:19:54,560 --> 00:19:57,260
Oh, that's where it gets complicated.

332
00:19:57,320 --> 00:19:59,590
Twenty business days? That's four weeks.

333
00:19:59,760 --> 00:20:01,830
Then we can move the stock
price up within four weeks.

334
00:20:02,960 --> 00:20:04,060
How?

335
00:20:04,530 --> 00:20:07,200
By making WIND go public.

336
00:20:08,270 --> 00:20:10,470
If that were possible, it
would've already happened.

337
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:13,439
We couldn't tell Chairman
Song that it wouldn't work out.

338
00:20:13,440 --> 00:20:14,980
So, we kept putting it
off, and this happened.

339
00:20:17,640 --> 00:20:18,680
Yes.

340
00:20:21,050 --> 00:20:22,050
Oh, boy.

341
00:20:22,480 --> 00:20:23,480
Even if you know it won't work,

342
00:20:23,481 --> 00:20:26,090
it still is so hard to speak the truth.

343
00:20:26,520 --> 00:20:29,820
Who would be willing to say that?

344
00:20:29,890 --> 00:20:33,160
If you say it, you'll get chewed out.

345
00:20:34,600 --> 00:20:36,400
It's like we're passing the bomb around.

346
00:20:37,770 --> 00:20:39,770
I like that. Passing the bomb around.

347
00:20:42,900 --> 00:20:44,070
Come on. Let's go.

348
00:20:44,970 --> 00:20:45,970
Sir.

349
00:20:46,940 --> 00:20:47,979
Chairman Song is heading out now.

350
00:20:47,980 --> 00:20:50,380
- Should I get the car ready?
- No, let's go up there.

351
00:20:50,580 --> 00:20:51,580
Pardon?

352
00:20:51,581 --> 00:20:53,180
Joo No's office. What floor is it on?

353
00:20:53,880 --> 00:20:55,720
- It's on the 13th floor. - Let's go.

354
00:20:56,350 --> 00:20:59,120
But you see many bicycles
along the Han River.

355
00:20:59,520 --> 00:21:00,850
Yes, so many.

356
00:21:01,390 --> 00:21:03,060
So, how come WIND's
bicycles didn't sell well?

357
00:21:03,220 --> 00:21:05,159
There are many bike
share programs these days.

358
00:21:05,160 --> 00:21:06,189
I see.

359
00:21:06,190 --> 00:21:08,030
They're practically free, aren't they?

360
00:21:10,060 --> 00:21:11,830
All bicycle companies
will go bankrupt at this rate.

361
00:21:12,770 --> 00:21:14,470
How could they win against
government-funded businesses?

362
00:21:15,600 --> 00:21:16,840
We're not trying to win here.

363
00:21:19,240 --> 00:21:20,870
- Sir. - Yes, hi.

364
00:21:23,040 --> 00:21:24,140
You heard too, right?

365
00:21:24,450 --> 00:21:26,350
If you're talking about WIND, yes.

366
00:21:26,950 --> 00:21:28,420
- I read the article. - I see.

367
00:21:29,250 --> 00:21:30,420
So, what do you think?

368
00:21:31,750 --> 00:21:33,720
It wasn't an easy
undertaking to begin with.

369
00:21:34,120 --> 00:21:36,120
Right. Everyone thinks it's not possible.

370
00:21:37,320 --> 00:21:39,560
But did every business go
bankrupt during the pandemic?

371
00:21:40,330 --> 00:21:42,600
Some businesses are actually
doing better after the pandemic.

372
00:21:42,900 --> 00:21:44,670
- Am I wrong? - No, you're right.

373
00:21:45,100 --> 00:21:47,670
But even if the COVID-19
pandemic had never happened,

374
00:21:48,040 --> 00:21:49,770
the bicycle industry would've struggled.

375
00:21:50,570 --> 00:21:51,770
What do you mean?

376
00:21:52,240 --> 00:21:53,769
With the bike share programs in place,

377
00:21:53,770 --> 00:21:55,710
more people are riding bikes these days,

378
00:21:56,040 --> 00:21:58,710
but most bicycle companies'
sales have dropped.

379
00:21:59,250 --> 00:22:00,280
Right, of course.

380
00:22:00,510 --> 00:22:02,549
The government is practically
offering free bike rides.

381
00:22:02,550 --> 00:22:04,119
So, who would buy a bike?

382
00:22:04,120 --> 00:22:05,750
They're running these
programs using tax money.

383
00:22:06,090 --> 00:22:07,720
How could you beat that? You know?

384
00:22:07,860 --> 00:22:08,860
Right.

385
00:22:09,020 --> 00:22:12,689
So, we need a strategy
to entice bike users...

386
00:22:12,690 --> 00:22:13,960
to want better bikes.

387
00:22:14,960 --> 00:22:16,400
With such a strategy,

388
00:22:17,230 --> 00:22:18,499
I believe the company...

389
00:22:18,500 --> 00:22:20,170
can actually thrive in the high-end market.

390
00:22:22,100 --> 00:22:23,170
Then...

391
00:22:25,610 --> 00:22:26,810
do you think you can do it?

392
00:22:33,280 --> 00:22:34,310
Yes?

393
00:22:35,350 --> 00:22:36,420
Yes, sir.

394
00:22:41,660 --> 00:22:43,460
The CEO used to be a professional archer.

395
00:22:43,860 --> 00:22:45,759
So, he started out in archery.

396
00:22:45,760 --> 00:22:48,660
Then with his expertise in carbon
materials, he expanded into cycling.

397
00:22:49,400 --> 00:22:51,329
They only handle carbon bikes,

398
00:22:51,330 --> 00:22:53,070
so they started focusing
on the high-end market.

399
00:22:57,040 --> 00:22:58,710
Any questions?

400
00:22:59,910 --> 00:23:01,440
Why did you say you could do it?

401
00:23:02,140 --> 00:23:03,480
We just had to keep our mouths shut.

402
00:23:03,540 --> 00:23:05,580
Tell me. Why did you do that?

403
00:23:07,150 --> 00:23:08,580
Because I think it can work.

404
00:23:10,180 --> 00:23:11,550
I'm used to this.

405
00:23:15,190 --> 00:23:17,220
(WIND)

406
00:23:30,740 --> 00:23:32,610
Oh, hello. Welcome.

407
00:23:32,740 --> 00:23:33,940
- Hello. - Hello.

408
00:23:34,070 --> 00:23:35,639
- I'm Park Rae Gyeong. - Hello.

409
00:23:35,640 --> 00:23:36,710
Thank you.

410
00:23:40,110 --> 00:23:42,219
Here, you see our archery bows...

411
00:23:42,220 --> 00:23:44,920
displayed in chronological order.

412
00:23:45,650 --> 00:23:48,120
And they're pictures of some important...

413
00:23:48,360 --> 00:23:50,260
or meaningful moments for the company.

414
00:23:51,060 --> 00:23:52,929
During the Olympic
Games, I always make sure...

415
00:23:52,930 --> 00:23:54,360
to watch the archery competitions.

416
00:23:55,060 --> 00:23:57,830
I'm always so fascinated
when I see them hit the target.

417
00:23:58,330 --> 00:24:00,770
It really is fascinating that
they can hit the bull's-eye.

418
00:24:01,300 --> 00:24:02,440
How do they do that?

419
00:24:02,940 --> 00:24:04,369
Do you have to be born with the talent?

420
00:24:04,370 --> 00:24:06,110
You can do it if you keep practising.

421
00:24:07,140 --> 00:24:09,210
But don't you need some
level of natural-born talent?

422
00:24:10,310 --> 00:24:11,710
Yes, you do.

423
00:24:12,510 --> 00:24:14,050
But being able to keep at it...

424
00:24:14,480 --> 00:24:16,720
is a more precious talent
than being naturally good at it.

425
00:24:17,880 --> 00:24:19,290
You were a professional archer too, right?

426
00:24:19,650 --> 00:24:22,690
I wasn't that good, though.

427
00:24:22,790 --> 00:24:24,060
I never won a medal.

428
00:24:24,560 --> 00:24:27,289
But the archery bows we
made won some gold medals.

429
00:24:27,290 --> 00:24:30,030
Doesn't that mean you've
won so many medals?

430
00:24:32,500 --> 00:24:33,500
Oh, right.

431
00:24:33,630 --> 00:24:36,900
This was when we took over DAICHI.

432
00:24:37,870 --> 00:24:40,540
DAICHI used to be the
number-one company, right?

433
00:24:40,640 --> 00:24:42,140
Yes, back in the 90s.

434
00:24:42,240 --> 00:24:43,909
But we beat them...

435
00:24:43,910 --> 00:24:45,450
and took over.

436
00:24:45,810 --> 00:24:47,780
Who's the person next to you?

437
00:24:49,520 --> 00:24:50,550
Oh, him.

438
00:24:50,880 --> 00:24:53,750
He made this blueprint.

439
00:24:53,950 --> 00:24:56,090
He was DAICHI's best engineer.

440
00:24:57,320 --> 00:25:00,860
So, this master gave you this blueprint?

441
00:25:00,990 --> 00:25:02,160
Yes, as a gift.

442
00:25:02,600 --> 00:25:04,630
And I gave him that slogan as a gift.

443
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:07,300
Did you write it yourself?

444
00:25:08,240 --> 00:25:09,770
When I was an archer,

445
00:25:10,070 --> 00:25:11,369
I practised calligraphy,
thinking it could help...

446
00:25:11,370 --> 00:25:12,870
improve my concentration.

447
00:25:15,710 --> 00:25:16,940
What does it say?

448
00:25:17,140 --> 00:25:18,350
"Ongojisin."

449
00:25:18,880 --> 00:25:21,480
Gain new insights by
learning from the past.

450
00:25:23,250 --> 00:25:24,380
What a cute child.

451
00:25:26,850 --> 00:25:29,790
Oh, that's his son whom he had quite late.

452
00:25:30,020 --> 00:25:31,630
He was so cute.

453
00:25:32,530 --> 00:25:33,590
I see.

454
00:25:37,200 --> 00:25:39,700
From here, you see our cycles.

455
00:25:40,270 --> 00:25:41,330
I see.

456
00:25:42,900 --> 00:25:44,640
How much does something like this cost?

457
00:25:46,240 --> 00:25:47,540
About 30,000 dollars.

458
00:25:49,840 --> 00:25:51,650
I guess some cycles are
more expensive than cars.

459
00:25:52,210 --> 00:25:53,280
Yes, I guess.

460
00:25:53,350 --> 00:25:55,719
I thought the expensive ones
would cost around 1,000 dollars.

461
00:25:55,720 --> 00:25:57,380
This is for professional cyclists.

462
00:25:58,090 --> 00:25:59,190
I see.

463
00:25:59,650 --> 00:26:02,560
It's widely known that professional
cyclists only ride WIND, right?

464
00:26:03,490 --> 00:26:04,590
Yes, of course.

465
00:26:05,030 --> 00:26:07,529
Even 0.1 or 0.01 seconds...

466
00:26:07,530 --> 00:26:09,160
could make or break their races,

467
00:26:09,400 --> 00:26:11,630
so they only ride the best of the best.

468
00:26:12,430 --> 00:26:14,329
But your sales will be limited
if you only sell your products...

469
00:26:14,330 --> 00:26:15,900
to professional cyclists.

470
00:26:18,110 --> 00:26:19,370
Well, that is...

471
00:26:20,670 --> 00:26:22,740
certainly a problem WIND should solve.

472
00:26:24,040 --> 00:26:25,150
So about that problem,

473
00:26:26,680 --> 00:26:27,780
let's solve it together.

474
00:26:28,010 --> 00:26:29,350
(Analysis Report on WIND)

475
00:26:30,250 --> 00:26:32,449
WIND has launched 12
models, and their prices range...

476
00:26:32,450 --> 00:26:33,850
from 5,000 dollars to 30,000 dollars.

477
00:26:34,390 --> 00:26:37,490
You'd think the cheapest
model would sell the most.

478
00:26:37,760 --> 00:26:40,030
But it was actually
the worst-selling model.

479
00:26:40,160 --> 00:26:42,660
All sports are competitive, you know.

480
00:26:43,060 --> 00:26:44,830
The same goes for equipment.

481
00:26:45,570 --> 00:26:47,530
No one likes the lowest-end model.

482
00:26:47,930 --> 00:26:48,999
I see.

483
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:52,039
WIND A is the cheapest
model, and the model...

484
00:26:52,040 --> 00:26:54,669
that's one tier above it has sold the most.

485
00:26:54,670 --> 00:26:55,680
That's right.

486
00:26:56,340 --> 00:26:58,010
That's the nature of sport.

487
00:26:58,610 --> 00:27:00,150
No one likes the tailender.

488
00:27:00,610 --> 00:27:02,020
Then what if WIND A...

489
00:27:03,320 --> 00:27:04,520
isn't the tailender?

490
00:27:05,350 --> 00:27:06,350
Pardon?

491
00:27:08,190 --> 00:27:09,959
(Product and Material Analysis)

492
00:27:09,960 --> 00:27:12,260
Bikes are categorized and rated
based on their frame materials.

493
00:27:13,060 --> 00:27:14,130
That's correct.

494
00:27:14,390 --> 00:27:17,160
Steel, aluminium, carbon. In that order.

495
00:27:17,460 --> 00:27:18,929
If you were to switch
from an aluminium model...

496
00:27:18,930 --> 00:27:20,369
from a different brand
to WIND's carbon model,

497
00:27:20,370 --> 00:27:21,640
you'd have to invest another 1,000 dollars.

498
00:27:21,770 --> 00:27:23,969
That 1,000 dollars is a hurdle
that is hindering people...

499
00:27:23,970 --> 00:27:26,810
from switching to a carbon
model from an aluminium one.

500
00:27:31,850 --> 00:27:35,080
Carbon bikes are on
a whole different level.

501
00:27:35,450 --> 00:27:38,020
You shouldn't compare
them to aluminium models.

502
00:27:38,220 --> 00:27:39,220
Right.

503
00:27:39,420 --> 00:27:41,420
So, WIND A is on a whole different level.

504
00:27:41,690 --> 00:27:43,460
What if we could sell it
in the 4,000-dollar range?

505
00:27:43,890 --> 00:27:45,760
In the competition against
the aluminium models,

506
00:27:46,360 --> 00:27:48,230
it'll win without fail, don't you think?

507
00:27:48,630 --> 00:27:49,860
It will definitely win.

508
00:27:50,600 --> 00:27:53,200
Yes, who'd ride an aluminium
bike if they're the same price?

509
00:27:53,630 --> 00:27:54,730
Everyone would ride a carbon bike.

510
00:27:55,740 --> 00:27:56,769
(Per Model Price Chart)

511
00:27:56,770 --> 00:27:57,770
Exactly.

512
00:27:57,870 --> 00:28:00,340
Then naturally, the consumers who
were going to buy aluminium models...

513
00:28:00,840 --> 00:28:02,440
would choose WIND instead.

514
00:28:05,080 --> 00:28:06,110
Well...

515
00:28:08,420 --> 00:28:10,050
I agree,

516
00:28:10,980 --> 00:28:12,050
but the thing is,

517
00:28:12,990 --> 00:28:15,790
it really isn't easy to
bring the price down.

518
00:28:16,760 --> 00:28:19,989
We barely managed to
bring it down to 5,000 dollars.

519
00:28:19,990 --> 00:28:22,060
We really can't bring it
down to 4,000 dollars.

520
00:28:24,330 --> 00:28:25,970
What if the market were to expand?

521
00:28:26,570 --> 00:28:28,900
Then you can manufacture
them on a mass scale, can't you?

522
00:28:29,600 --> 00:28:30,770
Well, possibly.

523
00:28:31,300 --> 00:28:35,710
The thing is, the frames
aren't the only important part.

524
00:28:36,040 --> 00:28:38,080
The gear is also very important.

525
00:28:38,750 --> 00:28:41,180
When it comes to bike gears,
SHIMIZ in Japan is the best.

526
00:28:41,850 --> 00:28:43,350
They have a patent too.

527
00:28:44,250 --> 00:28:46,119
They'll need to supply us with gears.

528
00:28:46,120 --> 00:28:49,660
If not, we can't make a lot
of them even if we want to.

529
00:28:50,220 --> 00:28:51,960
So, they're like semiconductors.

530
00:28:52,090 --> 00:28:53,160
That's right.

531
00:28:53,590 --> 00:28:55,300
SHIMIZ calls the shots.

532
00:28:55,900 --> 00:28:58,330
It'll be hard to secure enough units.

533
00:28:58,770 --> 00:29:02,040
We'll meet with SHIMIZ
and try to negotiate with them.

534
00:29:06,110 --> 00:29:08,940
Then it has to get sorted out by next week.

